# Use Case Page Brief Rules

## Visitor Intent

Every /use-cases visitor arrives with one of two entry points:
- **Google organic** — searched a specific keyword (e.g. "construction CVR software"), landing cold with no prior StoneRise context
- **Site navigation** — already on the site, self-selected into this use case, warmer but still evaluating

In both cases the intent is identical: does this solve my specific problem and is this the right product for me?

---

## Page Structure (Mandatory Order)

### 1. Hero
- H1 must exactly match or closely mirror the target search keyword
- Subheadline must describe the visitor's current situation in language they recognise from their own day
- Single CTA: "Book a Free Demo"

### 2. Problem Block — 3 pain points
- Each pain point must include the **consequence**, not just the symptom
  - BAD: "CSCS cards tracked on spreadsheets"
  - GOOD: "A worker with a lapsed card ends up on site and you find out during a CDM audit"
- Must feel written by someone who has done the job, not a software company guessing
- Use construction industry language naturally (RFQs, POs, CSCS, pay less notices, CVRs, QS, subcontract, package)

### 3. CTA (repeat)
- Repeat the "Book a Free Demo" CTA button after the problem block

### 4. Solution Block — 4 features
- Each feature = heading + one sentence of benefit
- Make the before/after workflow explicit, not just the feature name
  - BAD: "Automated PO creation"
  - GOOD: "A request is raised, approved, and the PO is built and sent to the supplier automatically — no manual document creation"

### 5. Differentiation Block — "Built for construction, not adapted for it"
- 2–3 lines positioning StoneRise against generic alternatives
- Do NOT list features here — this is a positioning statement
- Reference that Stelios and Michael are qualified QSs who ran construction businesses
- Example angle: "Unlike generic tools built for any industry, the workflows in Certify match how a construction commercial team actually operates — because they were designed by people who ran one"

### 6. Credibility Block
- "Built by QSs who ran construction businesses. Not generic software adapted for construction."
- Stelios Ioannou and Michael Loizias are qualified quantity surveyors with 10 years running construction businesses before building StoneRise.

### 7. FAQ Block — 3–4 questions
Address the practical fit and risk objections that prevent demo bookings:
- How long does it take to set up / get started?
- Does it integrate with Sage or our accounting software?
- Is it suitable for a business our size?
- What does the demo involve — is there any commitment?

Answers should be brief (2 sentences max each) and reassuring without being vague.

### 8. Final CTA Section
- Headline: specific to the page feature (e.g. "See Certify produce your CVRs from live project data")
- Body: qualifying offer (3 months free for qualifying contractors)
- CTA button: "Book a Free Demo"

---

## Writing Rules (Non-Negotiable)

- No dashes anywhere — no hyphens, em dashes, en dashes. Rephrase using commas or full stops.
- No generic SaaS language: "revolutionary", "game-changing", "all in one", "seamless", "powerful"
- No invented statistics — only approved proof points from rule 03
- Problem-first always — never mention the solution before the pain
- Short paragraphs — 2 sentences maximum per block
- Single CTA colour and label throughout — never vary the button text

---

## SEO Requirements

- Page title format: `[Feature Name] for [Audience] | StoneRise`
- Meta description: problem-led, 150 characters max, no invented stats
- H1 must match or mirror the target keyword
- Keywords used naturally throughout — not stuffed
- All /use-cases pages are indexed (no noindex)

---

## What These Pages Are NOT

- Not a feature catalogue — each page owns one problem and one solution
- Not the place to mention other StoneRise modules or apps
- Not the place to mention pricing
- Not a blog post — no long paragraphs, no background context, no history
